snippet.title: Python - Finance - Interactive Brokers
snippet.description: The Interactive Brokers API provides users a framework to manage their accounts, execute a trade, stream prices, and collect data. In this playlists, we explore how to use the Interactive Brokers API library, installation requirements, and exploring the endpoints. In this series, we will walk through the setup of the API, explore some of the endpoints related to market data, account information, and trading services. Additionally, we will explore some trading capabilities related to the API and also explore the streaming API.

snippet.title: Python APIs - TD Ameritrade Standard API
snippet.description:
TD Ameritrade offers a free API for its account holders for which they can use to manage their accounts, execute trades, stream data, and research different financial instruments. In this playlist, we explore how to use the TD Ameritrade API using Python, getting you access to the TD API, walking through the initial authentication workflow for the API, and exploring some of the endpoints.

snippet.title: Office JavaScript API - Excel
snippet.description:
Each of the office Applications has its own specific Host API. The Host API represents the API that you would use to access that particular application Object Model. For example, to use Excel in the Office JavaScript API, we would use the Office JavaScript API for Excel. The playlist you’re currently on covers the Office JavaScript API but from purely the Excel Perspective.

In this series, we cover different objects found inside the Excel API. These are objects like Pivot Tables, Workbooks, Worksheets, Ranges, and much more. With some objects, we will use far more than others like Excel Worksheets. With those objects, we will focus a little bit more time on them so we can understand how to navigate them, reference them, and manipulate them. That way, when we work with other objects, we can do so comfortably.

snippet.title: M Language - All
snippet.description: Power Query and Power BI are powerful tools that allow you to aggregate a wide variety of data sources and transform them into clean workable datasets. Behind the scenes, these two tools leverage the M Formula Language to provide quick and easy transformations through a wide variety of built-in functions. In this playlist, we introduce our new programming language and get some context about what it is and how it works. Once we have a solid foundation we will expand into different topics including the main data types, common operations, and then into scenarios where PowerQuery and PowerBI shine.

snippet.title: Office JavaScript API - Core
snippet.description:
To meet the new requirements of today’s developers and to ensure a more cohesive Microsoft Office experience. Microsoft has developed a new API that will allow developers to create and distribute Office Add-Ins that work not just on Windows operating systems but also Mac operating systems and the Office Online experience. However, to make a framework work across so many platforms meant abandoning the beloved VBA language in favor of more appropriate languages like TypeScript and JavaScript.

While some have been quick to dismiss the new API, the reality today is that you must use this new API to create Office Add-Ins that work across operating systems and platforms. Additionally, while the API presents a new learning curve for some, it will open up whole new opportunities to create more dynamic and responsive Office Add-Ins that will allow us to help take Office Application to their next levels.

In this playlist, you will find the Core Concepts necessary to get started using the Office JavaScript API so that you can start writing code that interacts with this new API. Additionally, we will cover new concepts specific to languages that are asynchronous and understand how this will impact the development process going forward. For editing purposes, a video will go over the new Script Lab Add-In can write, execute, and experiment with code directly in the host Office Application.

snippet.title: VBA - Excel - Charts
snippet.description: Excel is used heavily to graph data because of its flexibility and reliability when it comes to working with large data sets. Excel gives users the ability to control these chart objects from VBA with an extreme level of detail that focuses on control of the different components of a chart. In this series, we explore how to use the chart object in VBA and how to format a chart to match the style we desire.

snippet.title: VBA - Excel - Power Pivot
snippet.description: Power Pivot is an Excel Add-In that allows users to create Data Models but from within Excel. Data Models will enable us to take advantage of relationships between datasets and use them to help join separate data sets. However, being able to control Power Pivot from VBA is exceptionally challenging because there simply aren’t examples out there. However, I wanted to explore this different topic and see if we could shed some light on how the model works and how we can use it in our existing Excel workbooks.

snippet.title: VBA - Excel - Pivot Tables
snippet.description: Pivot Tables give users the ability to slice and dice data in more ways than they can imagine. Being able to master the use of Pivot Tables is a requirement for anyone who wants to be an Excel expert. However, for those who want the next challenge, then it’s time to explore Pivot Tables but from the VBA perspective. In this series, we explore the use of Pivot Tables, how to create them, how to select and work with the different components, and how to use them to automate the building of various reports.
